%DESC True/false questions on metric spaces
%HINC head.txt
%NOPARTIAL
%SETUP $a = random(2,9,1);
True or false:
Every set can be made into a metric space by defining a metric.
$BR
%RADIO
%CORRECT True
False
%END

True or false:
In a metric space \((X,d),\) if \(d(x,y) = 0 ,\) then \(x=y .\)
$BR
%RADIO
%CORRECT True
False
%END

True or false:
If \(X=$LB a,b $RB,\) for any \(r $GTS 0,\) we can define a metric such that
\(d(a,b) := r .\)
$BR
%RADIO
%CORRECT True
False
%END

True or false:
If \(X:=$LB a,b,c $RB,\) for any \(r $GTS 0,\) \(s $GTS 0,\) and \(t $GTS 0,\) we can define a metric such that
\(d(a,b) := r ,\)
\(d(a,c) := s ,\) and
\(d(b,c) := t .\)
$BR
%RADIO
True
%CORRECT False
%END

True or false:
In a metric space, the distance between any two points is finite.
$BR
%RADIO
%CORRECT True
False
%END

True or false:
If \((X,d)\) is a metric space and \(d'(x,y) := $a d(x,y), \) then \((X,d')\) is also a metric space.
$BR
%RADIO
%CORRECT True
False
%END

True or false:
If \((X,d)\) is a metric space and \(d'(x,y) := {\bigl(d(x,y)\bigr)}^2, \) then \((X,d')\) is also a metric space.
$BR
%RADIO
True
%CORRECT False
%END

True or false:
For any set \(X,\) we can define a metric \(d\) that makes \(X\) into a bounded set.
$BR
%RADIO
%CORRECT True
False
%END

True or false:
If \((X,d)\) is a metric space and \(S \subset X\) is a finite set, then \(S\) is a bounded
subset.
$BR
%RADIO
%CORRECT True
False
%END
